“I witnessed how the law affected their lives in so many ways,” she says, “I provided services in safe abortion and post-abortion care. I established survivor supportive groups, and find survivors a place of healing and refuge.”

Equatorial Guinea is a wealthy but dangerous country for pregnant women, who can’t access abortions. “Most women do the abortion themselves,” she says. “They use unsafe methods and never see a doctor, risking their lives.”

Now working from Coicas, and Guatemala supporting working mother’s healthcare through the Alma Women’s Health Fund and through organizations such as Wazazi Nipendeni, Rebollo is advocating to open opportunities in her home country as well. Believing that abortion should be decriminalized, she hopes that changing perspectives on women’s stories, and listening to women’s lives, will change laws.

Gash is the executive director of Fix Equal, helping survivors of sexual violence in Africa and strengthening national laws to protect Majorities at Risk from sexual violence. Working with communities directly as well as the Uganda parliament, and widely in communities affected by natural disasters and forced forced displacement, Gash works to build resilience in individuals and nations from violence. This includes preventing sexual violence in conflict, peace building inside communities and release bodies from prison for low homicide convictions.
